"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Kings chapters 6–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1kings-6-7.py

Ch6: Temple construction — ANE architectural parallels (Tell Tayinat, Ain Dara, Hazor),
     Phoenician cedar trade, the 480-year chronology debate, quarry silence, Eden imagery
Ch7: Temple furnishings and palace — Jachin/Boaz pillar parallels, the bronze Sea
     and cosmic-waters symbolism, Jordan Valley metallurgy, the 13 vs. 7 year disproportion

Key context:
- The Solomonic Temple was a triple-room 'Syrian' long-house temple type common in Syro-Palestine
- Phoenician craftsmen and cedar from Lebanon provided the technical and material backbone
- The 480-year chronology (6:1) is the primary anchor for OT chronology debates
- The bronze Sea (7:23-26) has direct parallels in Ugaritic and Canaanite water-basin installations
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS1 = {
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>The 480-year chronological note anchoring the Temple's founding to the fourth year of Solomon (ca. 966 BCE) is the central datum in OT chronology debates. If the Exodus occurred 480 years earlier, it dates ca. 1446 BCE — the 'high chronology' supported by this text (cf. Judg 11:26, which also implies a mid-15th-century Exodus). Proponents of a 'low chronology' (Exodus ca. 1270-1250 BCE, aligned with Ramesside Egypt) treat 480 as a schematic number (12 generations × 40 years). The theological intent is clear regardless: the Temple was not a sudden royal project but the culmination of the entire covenant history from Sinai. The month Ziv (Canaanite name for the second month, approximately April–May) placed the start of construction in the dry season, optimal for stone transport and foundation laying.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Temple's dimensions (60 × 20 × 30 cubits, approximately 90 × 30 × 45 feet) identify it as a 'Syrian temple' or 'long-house' type well attested in Syro-Palestinian archaeology. Near-exact parallels exist at: (1) Tell Tayinat (9th century BCE, northern Syria) — a triple-room temple with nearly identical proportions; (2) Ain Dara (12th–9th century BCE, northern Syria) — a large temple with a three-room plan and elaborate stone carvings of lions, sphinxes, and divine footprints in the threshold; (3) Hazor (LB II, ca. 1300 BCE) — a triple-room sanctuary in stratum 1A. The Solomonic Temple was thus architecturally recognizable to its Syro-Palestinian contemporaries while being distinctive in scale and decoration. The temple compared favorably with Assyrian temples of the same era (Assur, Nimrud) but was considerably smaller than the great Egyptian temples at Karnak and Luxor.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The vestibule (<em>ʾûlām</em>) extending 10 cubits from the front of the Temple was the public face of the building, visible from the courtyard. The 20-cubit width of the vestibule = the full width of the main hall, creating a facade 20 × 10 cubits. The threefold spatial progression — vestibule, main hall, inner sanctuary — encodes a theology of graduated access: from the accessible (vestibule) through the restricted (main hall, priests only) to the most restricted (inner sanctuary, high priest once annually). This spatial theology is explicit in Hebrews 9-10 as a typological structure for Christ's high priestly work.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The 'windows of fixed lattice-work' (<em>ḥallônê šᵉqûpîm ʾăṭûmîm</em>) are a distinctive architectural feature whose exact design remains debated. They appear to have been narrower on the outside and wider on the inside — reverse-battered windows — designed to admit light while maintaining sacred privacy. Egyptian temples typically admitted no natural light (symbolizing the sun-god's dominance within his own domain); Mesopotamian temples had clerestory windows. The Solomonic Temple's latticework windows admitted natural light while veiling the interior from casual view — a balance between openness and sanctity characteristic of Israelite theology (YHWH dwells in thick darkness, yet speaks to his people).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The three-story annex surrounding the Temple on three sides (north, south, west — but not east, the entrance side) provided approximately 90 rooms of varying size. The side rooms (<em>yāṣîaʿ</em>) served as storage for Temple equipment, priestly vestments, and offerings brought to the Temple. This annex structure has parallels at the Ain Dara temple (which also had side-chambers along three walls). The prohibition against penetrating the Temple's primary walls (v7) for the annex attachment reflects the same concern as the prohibition of iron tools at the building site — the sacred enclosure must not be violated by construction activity.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The stepped-ledge construction (<em>migraʿôṯ</em>) of the Temple walls — each story narrower than the one below — created the structural 'shoulders' on which the annex floors rested without beams penetrating the main walls. This construction technique required careful pre-planning: the ledges had to be built into the wall as the wall rose, not cut afterward. The same technique appears in Iron Age buildings throughout the Levant. The attention to structural detail in the narrative reflects the presence of official building archives that Solomon's scribes kept — ancient Near Eastern kings routinely commissioned detailed building records as statements of royal piety and capacity.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The prohibition of iron tools at the Temple site (<em>ʾăḇānîm šᵉlēmôṯ</em>, dressed/complete stones) has three historical dimensions: (1) Stone was dressed at Megiddo's quarries and transported to Jerusalem — a logistically demanding process that explains the Temple's 7-year construction time; (2) Iron was the metal of warfare (Exod 20:25; Deut 27:5: altar stones must be uncut by iron) — the Temple's construction deliberately excluded the implements of violence; (3) The silence at the building site contrasted with the noise of Egyptian and Mesopotamian temple constructions, which used slave labor with hammers and chisels on-site. The Solomonic Temple was built in a quality of silence unusual in the ancient world.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Access to the three-story annex via a trapdoor-and-spiral-staircase arrangement on the south side of the Temple reflects the standard Iron Age construction for accessing multi-story storage rooms without large public doorways. The right (south) side placement of the annex entrance maintained the Temple's eastward orientation — the main entrance faced east toward the rising sun, while service entrances and access points were on secondary sides. This arrangement ensured that the visual drama of the Temple (its massive entrance porch) faced the approaching worshiper without distraction from maintenance entrances.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The completion of the main shell (v9: cedar beams and planks covering the roof) represents the completion of the primary structural enclosure before interior finishing began. Ancient Near Eastern temples were typically built in two stages: structural enclosure, then interior finishing and consecration. The Solomonic Temple's two-stage construction is reflected in the narrative structure: vv1-10 describe the shell; vv14-38 describe the interior treatment. The cedar roof was the most expensive element of the shell construction, requiring imported timber from Lebanon transported overland and by sea (5:9).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The three-story annex's five-cubit per story height (total 15 cubits) alongside the Temple's 30-cubit height placed the annex at half the height of the Temple walls. The cedar beams connecting the annex to the Temple at each story level created a structural integration while maintaining the separation required by v7. The overall building footprint — the Temple with its attached three-story annex — was substantially larger than the tabernacle the Temple replaced, reflecting the transition from a portable wilderness sanctuary to a permanent royal capital's central shrine.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The mid-construction divine word (vv11-13) is a formally structured conditional oracle, likely preserved from prophetic archives alongside the building records. YHWH's intervention during the building process is theologically significant: the building does not itself guarantee divine presence; YHWH's covenantal faithfulness depends on Solomon's obedience. This structure — divine promise embedded in human endeavor — is characteristic of the Deuteronomistic theology that frames 1-2 Kings. The divine word here anticipates Solomon's prayer at the dedication (ch 8) and its terrible answer in ch 11 (YHWH's judgment on Solomon for his marriages).</p>",
    "12": "<p>The conditional formulation ('if you walk in my statutes… then I will fulfill my promise to David') is the theological signature of Deuteronomistic theology, the framework governing 1-2 Kings. The three terms — statutes (<em>ḥuqqôṯ</em>), ordinances (<em>mišpāṭîm</em>), commandments (<em>miṣwôṯ</em>) — together represent the full scope of Torah obligation. The promise to David (2 Sam 7:12-16) is conditional at the temple-level even if unconditional at the dynasty level. The Temple is thus not a trophy of Israel's faithfulness but a stake planted in history — its survival depends on covenant obedience. The Babylonian destruction of 586 BCE is the historical demonstration of this condition's violation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>YHWH's promise to 'dwell in the midst of the Israelites' and 'not abandon' them is the Temple theology in a sentence. The Hebrew concept of divine dwelling (<em>šāḵan</em>) is concrete: YHWH genuinely inhabits the Temple between the cherubim, making it the point where heaven and earth intersect. This is distinct from the Greek philosophical concept of divine omnipresence — YHWH chose to localize his dwelling. The later exile (2 Kgs 25) did not contradict this promise; Ezekiel's vision of the glory departing from the Temple (Ezek 10-11) showed that YHWH left before the Babylonians arrived — the Temple's destruction was the consequence of YHWH's prior departure, not his defeat.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The structural summary of v14 ('Solomon built the house and completed it') closes the outer-shell section and opens the interior description. In ancient building inscriptions (Assyrian, Babylonian), such summary statements mark the completion of major construction phases before the formal description of interior decoration and furnishing. The Kings narrative follows this same literary convention, reflecting the probable use of royal building archives as source material. The completeness formula (<em>wayyᵉkallēhû</em>) marks a milestone: the building exists; it now needs to be made worthy of its divine occupant.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The cedar paneling of the interior (floor to ceiling on walls, and v15b: overlaid the floor with cypress/<em>bᵉrôšîm</em>) was the primary luxury treatment distinguishing the Temple's interior from ordinary stone buildings. Cedar from Lebanon was the most prized building material in the ancient Near East — Ramesses II used it for temple doors; Nebuchadnezzar lined his palace rooms with it. The complete coverage of the stone walls with cedar created an organic, aromatic interior entirely unlike stone buildings. The cedar's natural oils and fragrance would have been pervasive — the Temple's interior had a sensory dimension (scent, texture, visual warmth) missing from cold stone sanctuaries.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The creation of the inner sanctuary (<em>debîr</em>) by a cedar partition (floor-to-ceiling planks, v16) at the rear 20 cubits of the Temple has been confirmed by comparative archaeology. The 20-cubit rear chamber at Tell Tayinat is nearly identical in proportion. At Ain Dara, the sanctuary's innermost room was separated by a stone threshold and low partition. The use of a wooden partition (rather than stone wall) within the Temple maintained the all-cedar interior while creating the sacred boundary. The debir's cedar floor (<em>wayyibᵉn ʿeśrîm ʾammāh</em>) was the first element installed — the floor before the walls — suggesting the construction sequence built the debir from the floor up within the already-enclosed building.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The 40-cubit main hall (<em>hêḵāl</em>) served as the space where priests performed the daily rituals: burning incense on the golden altar, trimming and refueling the lampstands, presenting the bread of the Presence on the table. Access was restricted to priests (non-Levites never entered the hêḵāl; the high priest alone entered the debir, once annually on Yom Kippur). The architectural proportion (40:20 for hêḵāl to debir = 2:1) maintained the same ratio as the tabernacle's holy place to most holy place (20:10 cubits). The Temple doubled all tabernacle dimensions while preserving all ratios — a deliberate architectural encoding of the tabernacle's ongoing theological validity within the Temple's expanded scale.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The carved botanical program on the cedar interior — gourds (<em>pᵉqāʿîm</em>) and open flowers (<em>pᵉṭûrê ṣîṣîm</em>) — was the most extensive carved decoration in the ancient Levant outside of major Egyptian temples. The close parallel at Ain Dara (where every surface carries carved decoration of divine footprints, lions, and sphinxes) confirms that elite Iron Age Syro-Palestinian temples were entirely carved and painted. The specifically botanical program of the Solomonic Temple (palms, flowers, gourds — all living plants) was theologically chosen to evoke Eden, distinguishing it from the animal and divine imagery of Canaanite temples. The Temple's carved program announced: this is where the garden was, and where it will be again.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The purpose statement for the inner sanctuary ('to receive the ark of the covenant of YHWH') identifies the Temple's relationship to the ark established at Sinai. The ark was not created for the Temple — the Temple was created for the ark. This theological priority is significant: the ark and the covenant it represented preceded and grounded the Temple. When the ark was carried into the completed Temple (8:6-9), the action completed the journey begun in the wilderness: the portable covenant box finally had a permanent resting place, just as the itinerant people had finally had a permanent land (cf. 2 Sam 7:1-2: David's original motivation for building the Temple was that the ark was in a tent).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The perfect cube of the Holy of Holies (20 × 20 × 20 cubits) is the most geometrically significant feature of the Temple. In ancient Near Eastern cosmology, the cube represented the perfection and totality of the divine realm. The Assyrian inner sanctuaries at Nimrud and Assur were also proportionally cube-like. The Solomonic debir's perfect cube, overlaid entirely with gold, created the visual impression of a golden box — a massive version of the gold-overlaid ark inside it. The Rev 21:16 New Jerusalem's perfect cube (12,000 stadia × 12,000 stadia × 12,000 stadia) explicitly echoes this symbolism at cosmic scale.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The gold overlay of the Temple interior (<em>zāhāb sāgûr</em>, refined/pure gold) has a rough Solomonic-era parallel in the gold-lined inner rooms of Egyptian temples, but no exact parallel in Syro-Palestinian archaeology. The sheer quantity of gold used (vv21-22, 28, 30, 32, 35) was extraordinary — ancient building accounts from Egypt and Mesopotamia list temple gold by weight, and the Solomonic accounts (1 Chr 22:14: David prepared 100,000 talents of gold) suggest a scale rivaling the great Egyptian religious complexes. The archaeological record has not preserved any Solomonic-era gold, as the Temple was stripped first by Shishak (14:25-26), then by later kings, and finally destroyed by Babylon.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The cedar altar before the debir's entrance (v22b: 'the cedar altar that belonged to the inner sanctuary') was the incense altar — smaller than the bronze altar in the outer court, dedicated to daily incense burning. The tabernacle's incense altar (Exod 30:1-10) was gold-overlaid acacia wood; the Temple's was cedar (the structural wood of the interior) overlaid with gold. The altar's cedar construction connects it to the overall interior aesthetic rather than to the outer-court bronze furnishings, marking it as an inner-Temple object while its gold overlay connected it to the divine presence it faced.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The two olive-wood cherubim (10 cubits each, with 10-cubit wingspans) are the most archaeologically paralleled Temple feature. Cherubim — composite winged divine guardians — appear throughout the ancient Near East: Assyrian lamassu (winged bull-men guarding palace gates), Egyptian sphinxes (winged lions with human heads), and specifically Canaanite/Phoenician cherub-throne depictions at Megiddo (the 'Megiddo ivories,' ca. 1200 BCE, show a king on a cherub-throne), Byblos, and Hamath. The iconography of the cherub-throne was standard royal imagery in Syro-Palestine, making the Solomonic Temple's cherub-throne immediately recognizable as a divine palace. The OT's designation of YHWH as '<em>yōšēḇ hakkᵉrûḇîm</em>' (enthroned on the cherubim) uses precisely this iconographic vocabulary.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Each cherub's 10-cubit wingspan (5 cubits per wing) created winged guardians proportioned to fill the Holy of Holies completely when outstretched. The use of olive wood (<em>ʿaṣê šāmen</em>) for the cherubim was a practical choice: olive wood is extremely dense (800-900 kg/m³), hard, and resistant to insect damage — appropriate for permanent sacred objects not subject to replacement. The combination of dense olive wood with gold overlay created objects of extraordinary durability and visual richness. The Ain Dara temple's stone-carved cherubim on the threshold and inner walls represent the decorative parallel, though the Solomonic ones were free-standing sculptures.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The identical dimensions of both cherubim (explicitly confirmed in v25) reflect the standard ANE principle of paired divine guardians: the guardian cherubim at temple entrances and sacred spaces were always paired and identical, representing the complete guardian presence without hierarchy. Paired sphinxes at Egyptian temple gates, paired lamassu at Assyrian palace gates, and paired cherubim in the tabernacle (Exod 25:18-20) all express this principle. The identical dimensions ensure that the theological statement the cherubim make is symmetric: divine protection extends equally in all directions.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The 10-cubit height of the cherubim (approximately 15 feet) placed them slightly taller than half the height of the Holy of Holies (30 feet). The visual proportions would have been stunning: entering the debir (had anyone done so), the viewer would have been dwarfed by two golden winged creatures whose combined wingspan covered every inch of the 20-cubit width, standing under a ceiling just 15 feet above their outstretched wings. Ancient Near Eastern sacred spaces were designed to produce awe through scale — the experience of human smallness before divine magnitude was architecturally engineered into the Temple.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The positioning of the cherubim — outer wings touching the walls, inner wings touching each other — created the covering canopy over the ark's position. The ark resting beneath the cherubim' outstretched wings was the spatial realization of Psalm 91:4 ('He will cover you with his pinions; under his wings you will find refuge'). The ark functioned as YHWH's footstool (1 Chr 28:2; Ps 132:7) while the cherubim formed his throne. The entire debir was thus architecturally structured as a divine throne room — the most sacred space in Israel visualized as the seat of the divine king.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The gold overlay of the olive-wood cherubim completed the visual language of the Holy of Holies: everything gold, everything oversized from a human perspective, everything dedicated to a single theological purpose. The technique of overlaying wooden religious objects with gold has parallels in the wooden gold-overlaid statues of Egyptian deities (though the Israelite cherubim were architectural, not deity-representations) and in the gold-overlaid ark itself. The total effect — gold floor, gold walls, gold ceiling, gold cherubim — created the impression of entering a space made of light.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The carved decorative program on all interior walls (cherubim, palm trees, open flowers) has its closest parallel at the Ain Dara temple in northern Syria, where the interior walls and threshold carry extensive carved relief of divine footprints, lions, and sphinxes. The specific combination of cherubim, palms, and flowers in the Solomonic Temple is unique in ANE temple decoration and reflects a deliberate choice: the Eden vocabulary (garden guardians, garden trees, garden blossoms) rather than the storm-deity or warrior imagery of neighboring temples. The Temple was designed to evoke paradise regained rather than divine power over chaos, though both themes are present in the broader Solomonic building complex.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The gold floor is unique among known ANE temple floors. Most temple floors were stone (limestone, basalt), occasionally wood. A floor of gold overlay — applied to the cedar boards that lay on the stone subfloor — would have created a reflective, luminous walking surface. In procession into the Temple, the priest's feet would have walked on gold, surrounded by gold walls and gold furnishings, beneath carved gold cherubim. The sensory environment of the completed Temple interior was designed to communicate: you are in YHWH's presence, and his presence is glorious beyond human imagination.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The five-sided door frame of the debir's entrance (<em>mezûzōṯ ḥamēšîṯ</em>) is architecturally unusual. A five-sided frame suggests a pentagonal opening — possibly a doorway with a slightly arched or canted upper frame rather than a standard rectangular opening. Alternatively, <em>ḥamēšîṯ</em> may describe a five-section molding around the door. The precise architectural form has not been reconstructed with certainty. What is clear is that the debir's entrance was architecturally differentiated from the main hall's entrance (v33: four-sided frame) — the distinctiveness of the opening encoding the distinctiveness of the space beyond.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The olive-wood doors of the debir's entrance carried the full interior decorative program: carved cherubim, palms, and flowers, with gold fitted over the carved relief. The continuity of the carved program from the walls to the doors to the cherubim created visual coherence: everywhere the worshiper looked within the Temple was the same vocabulary of Eden guardianship, covenant abundance, and divine beauty. The doors' olive-wood material matched the cherubim — the same sacred wood for the threshold guardians and the chamber guardians.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The four-sided (rectangular) frame of the main hall's entrance compared with the five-sided frame of the debir's entrance created an architectural gradient from ordinary to sacred. The main hall's rectangular doorframe was the standard door form; the debir's unusual pentagonal frame marked it as exceptional. The distinction in door frames is one of several architectural markers distinguishing the hêḵāl from the debîr: different wood (cypress vs. olive), different frame shape (rectangular vs. pentagonal), different access (priests regularly vs. high priest once annually on Yom Kippur).</p>",
    "34": "<p>The cypress (<em>bᵉrôšîm</em>) double-leaf doors of the main hall were each divided into two hinged panels that could open partially for normal access. The folding-door system is attested in ANE palace and temple architecture and allowed flexible management of the sacred threshold: fully open for major processions, half-open for daily priestly ministry. Cypress is a durable, aromatic wood less prestigious than cedar (which lined the interior) but well-suited for doors — resistant to warping and with natural pest-repellent properties. The consistent use of aromatic woods (cedar interior, cypress doors, olive-wood inner doors and cherubim) created an olfactory dimension to the Temple experience.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The technique of hammering gold to conform precisely to the underlying carved relief (<em>mûšāh ʿal-hamᵉḥuqqeh</em>) represents advanced goldsmithing practiced by Phoenician craftsmen of the period. The Phoenicians (Tyrians) were the Mediterranean world's most skilled metal workers of the 10th century BCE; their carved ivory work (notably the 'Megiddo ivories' from the Solomonic period) shows precisely this technique of fitting gold and other materials over carved wooden bases. Hiram of Tyre (ch 5) provided not just cedar but the craftsmen capable of executing this level of decorative work.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The inner court surrounding the Temple (stone courses alternating with cedar beams, 3:1 ratio) created the sacred precinct separating the Temple proper from the outer court. This construction method — alternating courses of stone and timber — is attested at sites including Megiddo and is characteristic of Phoenician-influenced construction in 10th-century Syro-Palestine. The timber courses provided structural flexibility (the wood absorbs stress that would crack all-stone walls in seismic events), while the stone courses provided permanence. Jerusalem sits in a seismically active region, and the mixed-masonry technique was well-adapted to local conditions.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The founding of the Temple in the month of Ziv (April–May, the second month) took advantage of the dry season's end — the spring rains had consolidated the soil, transport was easier, and the building season was just beginning. The Canaanite month names (Ziv in v37, Bul in v38) appear only here in the OT and reflect the pre-exilic use of Phoenician calendar terminology, consistent with the Solomonic period's heavy Phoenician cultural influence. Post-exilic texts use numbered months or later Babylonian names (Nisan, Iyyar, etc.). The Phoenician month names in the Temple account are thus authentic chronological markers of the 10th-century source material.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The seven-year construction period (ca. 966-959 BCE) for a building of the Temple's scale was impressive but not unusual for ANE royal temple projects. Assyrian kings regularly recorded temple constructions of 3-7 years for major projects. What distinguished the Solomonic project was its quality: no royal project of comparable scale in Syro-Palestine during the Iron Age used comparable quantities of gold, bronze, and cedar. The Temple was, within its regional context, extraordinary. The seven-year completion connects the building to the creation week in Israelite theology — just as YHWH built the cosmos in seven days, Solomon built YHWH's earthly residence in seven years. The number is almost certainly recorded exactly, not schematized.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>Solomon's palace complex requiring thirteen years (compared to the Temple's seven) is noted by the Deuteronomistic narrator as a significant inversion. In ancient Near Eastern royal ideology, the temple precedes the palace — the king builds for his god first, then for himself. Nebuchadnezzar's inscriptions consistently record temple restorations before palace projects. Solomon's palace complex, though begun after the Temple (the Temple was completed first), taking nearly twice as long signals a growing royal priority for self-glorification. The 'House of the Forest of Lebanon,' the Hall of Pillars, the Hall of the Throne, and Solomon's own quarters formed an elaborate compound that dwarfed the Temple in area if not in sanctity.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The 'House of the Forest of Lebanon' (100 × 50 × 30 cubits) served multiple functions in Solomon's administrative system. 1 Kgs 10:17 identifies it as an armory for the 500 gold shields; Isa 22:8 calls it 'the House of the Forest of Lebanon' in the context of Hezekiah's military preparations, indicating its armory function persisted. The building's name came from its cedar forest of 45 pillars — the interior would have resembled a cedar grove. This type of hypostyle hall (columned hall) was used throughout the ancient Near East for royal reception, storage, and administrative functions. At 100 × 50 cubits, it was more than twice the Temple's ground area, expressing Solomon's imperial scale.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The hypostyle design of the House of the Forest of Lebanon — cedar pillars bearing cedar beams supporting a cedar ceiling — reflects the Phoenician architectural tradition imported with Hiram's craftsmen. Phoenician woodworking was the premier craft of the 10th century BCE; the technique of using cedar columns as structural elements appears at Kuntillet Ajrud and other sites in the period. The visual effect of 45 cedar columns rising to a cedar ceiling created the forest impression that gave the building its name. Cedar was both the most expensive and the most aromatic building material — the palace complex was saturated with the cedar scent.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The three rows of windows on each side of the House of the Forest of Lebanon (window rows above each of the three tiers of columns, or perhaps three sets of paired windows on each facade) provided the clerestory lighting that made the hypostyle hall usable as a reception space. Large ceremonial halls required substantial natural lighting for the diplomatic functions Solomon conducted there: receiving foreign delegations (the Queen of Sheba, 10:1-13), displaying royal treasures (10:4-5), and hosting formal state occasions. The architectural vocabulary of the palace — lattice windows, cedar pillars, matched frames — was deliberately consistent with the Temple to present palace and Temple as a unified royal-divine complex.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The standardized square frames of all the palace's doorways and window openings reflect the precision demanded of Phoenician craftsmen by Solomonic building standards. Consistent modular dimensions across a building complex indicate a sophisticated measuring and planning system — the same system used for the Temple. The consistent terminology (doorways, window-frames, <em>šāqep</em>) between palace and Temple descriptions reflects the unified building vocabulary of Solomon's architectural program, which drew on the same craftsmen, materials, and design principles for both sacred and royal structures.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Hall of Pillars (50 × 30 cubits) served as the formal entrance vestibule to the royal complex's throne hall. This transitional space — larger than a mere corridor but smaller than the main halls — was characteristic of ANE palace design: a formal transition zone between the exterior courtyard and the inner royal spaces. The Assyrian palace at Nimrud had a similar sequence of transitional halls before the throne room. Solomon's colonnaded hall made the approach to the throne a visually imposing experience — columns lining both sides, a canopied ceiling above, creating a processional corridor that oriented visitors toward royal authority.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The throne hall where Solomon dispensed justice was the functional center of the Solomonic administrative system. The later description (10:18-20) of Solomon's elaborate gold and ivory throne gives the space its context: a room designed for the visible performance of royal judgment, with the great throne as its focal point. 1 Kgs 3:16-28 (the two prostitutes and the disputed infant) shows Solomon's judicial function operating through direct royal access — the throne hall was the apex of Israel's legal system. The cedar-lined judicial space communicated that justice in Israel was conducted in a space consecrated by the same sacred cedar that lined the Temple — royal justice and divine justice were architecturally linked.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The separation of Solomon's personal quarters from the judicial and reception halls reflects the standard ANE royal palace organization: public (reception, armory, administrative) → semi-public (audience chambers) → private (royal apartments). Pharaoh's daughter's separate house within the palace complex (v8b) is historically remarkable: Egyptian royal daughters were never given in diplomatic marriage to foreign kings — this policy had held for centuries. Solomon's marriage to a pharaoh's daughter represents either an exceptional elevation of his regional status or a period of Egyptian dynastic weakness (possibly during the reign of Siamun, ca. 978-959 BCE, who gave his daughter and the city of Gezer as dowry, 9:16).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The use of 'costly stones' (<em>ʾăḇānîm yᵉqārôṯ</em>) dressed with saws throughout the palace construction has been partially confirmed by archaeology. Quarry marks and dressed limestone blocks from the 10th century BCE have been found at Megiddo, Jerusalem (the 'stepped stone structure'), and Gezer. The quarrying and transport of large dressed blocks required sophisticated logistics: quarry sites (possibly at Beit Hanina north of Jerusalem), cutting teams, oxcart transport on prepared roads, and on-site lifting equipment. The same infrastructure used for the Temple served the palace complex, explaining the overlapping 20-year construction period (Temple 7 years, Palace 13 years, total construction era ca. 966-946 BCE).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Foundation stones of 8-10 cubits (12-15 feet) in length for the palace are consistent with Iron Age palace construction in the Levant. The 'Solomonic gates' at Megiddo, Hazor, and Gezer (Yigael Yadin's identification, still debated) used foundation stones of comparable dimensions. The emphasis on massive foundation stones in the ancient Near East served both structural and symbolic purposes: a king's building was judged by its permanence, and permanent buildings required foundations that would outlast generations. Solomon's palace foundations were designed to communicate dynastic permanence — the same message the Davidic covenant promised.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The alternating stone-and-cedar superstructure of the palace walls (v11) uses the same 3:1 ratio as the Temple's inner court (6:36). The deliberate consistency between palace and Temple construction methods — same stone types, same timber ratios, same craftsmen — created a visual and material unity between the two complexes on Jerusalem's eastern ridge. From a distance, the palace compound and the Temple compound would have appeared as a single integrated architectural statement — Solomon's divine and royal dwelling built to identical standards and materials.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The great outer court surrounding the entire Solomonic complex (palace buildings plus Temple precinct) was the most public space in Jerusalem. The alternating stone-and-cedar construction of the outer court walls (same 3:1 ratio as both the inner Temple court and the palace walls) visually unified the entire complex. Archaeological surveys of the eastern hill of Jerusalem suggest that the Solomonic complex occupied the northern extension of the City of David — what would later become the Temple Mount (Haram al-Sharif). The outer court wall defined the boundaries of YHWH's compound within which both the palace and Temple were enclosed — the entire complex was, in a sense, YHWH's property.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The summoning of Hiram (Huram-abi in Chronicles) from Tyre to supervise the Temple's bronze work reflects the Phoenician monopoly on advanced metallurgy in 10th-century BCE Syro-Palestine. Tyre was the commercial and craft center of the eastern Mediterranean; its artisans worked in bronze, gold, purple dye, glass, and ivory. The Phoenician-Israelite alliance (sealed by Hiram king of Tyre's treaty with both David and Solomon) gave Israel access to the Mediterranean craft network that included Egyptian, Aegean, and Cypriot techniques. The specific summons of a named craftsman from a named city reflects a professional guild system in which master craftsmen were known by reputation across national boundaries.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Hiram's mixed heritage (Tyrian father, Naphtalite mother) positioned him ideally as a cultural bridge between Phoenician craft expertise and Israelite religious requirements. The explicit comparison to Bezalel (Exod 31) — both 'filled with wisdom, understanding, and skill' — signals that the author of Kings viewed the Temple's construction as a direct continuation of the tabernacle tradition. The divine giftedness required for tabernacle construction (the Spirit's filling of Bezalel for sacred craft work) was still required for Temple construction — the continuity of craft wisdom is the continuity of divine enablement for sacred space. Hiram's Gentile heritage within an Israelite-commissioned project anticipates the eschatological pattern of Gentile inclusion in the building of the divine dwelling (Isa 60:10-11).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The two bronze pillars (18 cubits tall each, 12 cubits in circumference) were cast in the Jordan Valley clay beds (v46). Their casting required hollow-column bronze-casting technology: a clay core, wax or sand outer mold, and sustained bronze pouring at approximately 1000°C. The Phoenician craftsmen of Hiram's team had access to Mediterranean bronze-casting techniques refined over centuries of production (Cyprus was the bronze-casting center of the ancient Mediterranean, and 'Cyprus' etymologically derives from 'copper'). The scale of the pillars — 18 cubits, approximately 27 feet tall — would have made them among the largest free-standing bronze castings known in the 10th century BCE.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The capitals (<em>kaptōrôṯ</em>) atop each pillar (5 cubits tall each) were cast separately from the pillar shafts and attached after installation. The separate casting and attachment of capitals was standard practice in ANE monumental architecture: the column was erected first, then the capital placed atop it. The capitals' lattice-and-pomegranate decorative program (vv17-20) was the most visible element of the pillars when approached from the Temple court — worshipers would have seen the decorated capitals towering above them as they entered the vestibule.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The lattice-work (<em>śᵉḇāḵôṯ</em>) and chain decorations on the pillar capitals reflect Phoenician metalwork traditions that combined open network patterns with hanging decorative elements. Phoenician ivories and metalwork from the 10th-9th century BCE show similar open-lattice designs. The 'seven' chains per capital may reflect a symbolic use of the number seven (completeness/divine perfection) in the decorative program, consistent with the Temple's broader use of sevenfold patterns (seven-branched lampstand, seven-day dedication feast).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The 200 pomegranates (<em>rimmōnîm</em>) on each capital (two rows × approximately 100 per row) made the capitals visually dense with the pomegranate motif. The pomegranate was the most prominent botanical symbol in Solomonic decorative arts: on the priestly robes (Exod 28:33), on the Temple interior walls (6:18), on the pillar capitals, and as standalone decorative elements. In Canaanite iconography, the pomegranate was associated with fertility and abundance — its many seeds symbolized the covenant blessings of numerous offspring and agricultural plenty. The Temple's pomegranate program converted the fertility iconography of the region into a covenant-blessing statement.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The lily-design capitals in the portico (<em>maʿăśēh šôšan</em>, four cubits tall) represent the formal Phoenician lily capital that was the standard decorative element on Syro-Palestinian temple entrances. Lily capitals appear on Phoenician bronze stands (like the Temple stands, vv27-37), on Cypriote temple furniture, and in Phoenician ivory work. The 'lily' in ANE art could represent either the lotus (Egyptian origin) or the indigenous Palestinian lily — both were symbols of beauty and divine presence. The lily-crowned pillars framing the Temple entrance created a formal threshold marked by the covenant's floral vocabulary.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The 400 pomegranates on the two pillar capitals (200 per capital) are confirmed in the post-Temple archaeological record by Jeremiah's description of the dismantled columns (Jer 52:22-23). Jeremiah records 96 visible pomegranates per side (facing outward) plus additional ones on the lattice network — the 200 per capital total includes those facing in multiple directions. This independent confirmation (Jeremiah writing ca. 580 BCE about the columns being taken to Babylon) validates the Kings building record's accuracy at the level of specific decorative details.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The names of the pillars — Jachin ('He establishes') and Boaz ('In him is strength') — are the most theologically interpreted architectural features in the OT. Standing at the Temple entrance, these named pillars greeted every worshiper with a declaration: YHWH establishes in his strength. Archaeological parallels for named entrance pillars exist at Cyprus (two named columns at the Paphos temple) and in Egyptian temple inscriptions where entrance obelisks carry royal name-dedications. But the Solomonic naming practice is distinctive: the names are not the king's name but theological statements about YHWH's character. Passing between Jachin and Boaz, every worshiper physically entered through a declaration of divine covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The lily-work tops completing the pillar capitals created a botanical crown for the Temple's entrance — the visual culmination of the pomegranate-and-lattice program ascending from the base of the capitals to the lily crowns. The formal completion notice ('the work of the pillars was finished') follows the pattern of the ANE building inscription: each major element is described, completed, and summarized before the next element begins. This careful narrative accounting reflects the use of official royal building records, preserved in the Temple archives, as the source for the Kings narrative.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The bronze Sea (<em>hayyām mûṣāq</em>) had direct parallels in ANE sacred architecture. The most relevant parallel is the large water basin found at the temple of Ain Dara in Syria. More broadly, large bronze or stone basins filled with water appear at Ugarit (the 'lakonos' or sacred basin) and in various Canaanite temple contexts. The choice of the term <em>yām</em> (sea) for the Temple's water basin is theologically deliberate: it invokes YHWH's dominion over the primordial chaotic sea (<em>yam</em> in Canaanite mythology was the sea-god defeated by Baal; YHWH defeated the sea at the Exodus, Ps 74:13-14). The Temple's Sea was the waters of chaos subdued, tamed, and made to serve the God of Israel's purification purposes.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The gourd motif (<em>pᵉqāʿîm</em>) in two rows under the Sea's rim was the same botanical element as in the Temple interior (6:18) and on the high priest's robe (Exod 28:33: pomegranates and bells alternating). The consistent appearance of the same botanical motifs (gourds, palms, lilies, pomegranates, flowers) across all scales of the Temple decorative program — from the carved walls to the cast bronze furnishings to the woven priestly vestments — reflects a deliberate and unified iconographic program. Everything in the Temple spoke the same visual language: the covenant garden, the land of abundance, YHWH's presence in the midst of his people.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The twelve bronze oxen supporting the Sea are among the most discussed features of the Temple's iconographic program. In Canaanite art, the bull/ox was the primary symbol of fertility, strength, and divine power — Baal was depicted as a bull in Ugaritic iconography. The use of twelve oxen (rather than the typical Canaanite mythological number) reinterpreted the ox-as-divine-symbol through the lens of Israel's twelve tribes: the cosmic waters (Sea) rested on the covenant community (twelve tribes), organized according to the four compass points (YHWH's universal sovereignty). The twelve oxen 'baptized' a Canaanite iconographic motif into Israelite covenantal theology.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The Sea's capacity of 2,000 baths (approximately 12,000 gallons; the 3,000 of 2 Chr 4:5 may reflect a different measurement or the full vs. working capacity) represented an enormous quantity of water maintained at the Temple. The logistical challenge of keeping the Sea filled — Jerusalem's water supply was limited to the Gihon Spring and seasonal cisterns — suggests either that the Sea was not filled to capacity regularly, or that it was connected to cisterns fed by the annual rains. The Sea was used for priestly washing (2 Chr 4:6), requiring regular access. The lily-rim design suggests the vessel was also an aesthetic centerpiece, not merely functional storage.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The ten wheeled bronze stands (<em>mᵉkônôṯ</em>) represent some of the most sophisticated bronze casting of the 10th century BCE. Four wheeled stands of similar design have been found at sites in Cyprus (Enkomi, Kourion) dating to the 12th-11th centuries BCE, showing that the wheeled laver-stand was a recognized temple furniture type in the eastern Mediterranean. The Cypriote examples are smaller than the Solomonic stands (approximately 1-2 cubits tall vs. 3 cubits) but share the same design elements: open-frame panels with animal and botanical decoration, four wheels with axles, and a basin-rim at the top. The Solomonic stands represent the largest and most elaborate examples of this furniture type known.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The detailed description of the stands' construction (vv28-37) is the most technically precise passage in the Temple building account. The specificity — crossbars, square frames, panels, corner pillars, wreaths — suggests the source was an actual technical drawing or craftsman's specification document. Ancient Near Eastern craftsmen used templates and specifications for repeated production of identical objects; the ten identical stands (v37) would have required such documentation. The Kings narrative's preservation of this technical data indicates that official Temple archives kept craftsmen's specifications alongside building accounts and inventories.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The three motifs on the stand panels — lions, oxen, and cherubim — are the same three figures that appear in Ezekiel's throne-chariot vision (Ezek 1:10: lion, ox, man/cherub, eagle) and in Rev 4:7 (the four living creatures). The mobile stand's design thus encoded the same symbolic vocabulary as the later theophanic vision: the divine chariot (<em>merkāḇāh</em>) is present in miniature on each of the ten mobile stands. The Solomonic Temple's furnishings anticipated the prophetic vision of the divine throne-chariot that would be fully revealed to Ezekiel at the Chebar canal — the Temple was, in its furnishings, already a representation of the celestial reality.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The four bronze wheels of each stand (<em>ʾôpannîm</em>) are the most archaeologically significant detail connecting the Temple stands to Ezekiel's vision. In Ezekiel 10:9-13, the divine chariot's wheels are described with the same term (<em>ʾôpannîm</em>) and the same 'wheel within a wheel' geometry. The Solomonic craftsmen did not design the stands to prefigure Ezekiel's vision; rather, both the stands and Ezekiel's vision drew on the same symbolic vocabulary of divine mobility — YHWH is not stationary, his chariot moves, and the Temple's furnishing system participated in representing that mobility. The stands' wheels moved the water of purification to where it was needed — divine grace, like divine presence, goes where YHWH wills.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The detailed specification of the stand's interior measurements (opening 1.5 cubits in diameter within a capital 1.5 cubits tall) reflects the same precision as the tabernacle measurements in Exod 25-27. The tabernacle was built to exact divine specifications (<em>mišpāṭ</em>, according to the pattern shown on the mountain); the Temple and its furnishings were built to the same standards of exactness. In both cases, the precision communicates that sacred space is not approximate but carefully ordered — the God who created the cosmos with mathematical precision requires his house to be built with comparable exactness.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The wheelbase design of the stands — four wheels under the lower frame, axles (<em>yāḏôṯ</em>) integral to the stand structure — reflects advanced bronze-casting engineering. The wheels had to bear the weight of the stand, the laver (when filled with approximately 240 gallons of water = approximately 1,000 kg), and the stand's own substantial bronze mass. The Cypriote parallels show that such stands were used for actual transport, not merely decorative display. The Solomonic stands were functional working implements, moved regularly in the course of priestly service.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The chariot-wheel construction method for the stand wheels reflects the most sophisticated wheel design available in the Iron Age — spoked wheels with bronze rim, hub, and spokes, assembled like war chariot wheels. The war chariot was the dominant military technology of the 10th century BCE, and its wheel design represented the engineering summit of the period. Repurposing war chariot engineering for Temple service stands was a deliberate inversion: the technology of warfare adapted to the service of divine worship. The same pattern appears in the Temple's structural use of iron (war metal) for door hinges and the Hiram craftsmen's bronze-casting skills (weapon technology for sacred furnishings).</p>",
    "34": "<p>The four structural 'shoulders' (<em>kêṯpôṯ</em>) at the corners of each stand connected the upper decorative frames to the lower wheel-bearing frame. The anatomical vocabulary ('shoulders') for structural joints is characteristic of ANE architectural terminology, which regularly used body parts for building elements: <em>peh</em> (mouth/opening), <em>yāḏ</em> (hand/shaft), <em>kātēp</em> (shoulder/corner), <em>rōʾš</em> (head/top). This body vocabulary encoded the ancient Near Eastern belief that buildings were living organisms — especially sacred buildings, which were understood as the 'body' of the divine resident.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The half-cubit circular rim at the top of each stand (the basin-seat) was the interface between the mobile stand and the stationary laver. The basin could be placed and removed from the stand for cleaning, replacement, or ritual repositioning. The functional modularity of the stand-laver system gave the Temple's priestly service considerable operational flexibility — the arrangement of lavers could be adjusted according to the type and volume of sacrifice being conducted. This practical flexibility within a fixed ritual framework reflects the balance between liturgical order and responsive worship that characterized Temple service.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The stand panels' carved decoration (cherubim, lions, palms) is confirmed by the Cypriote parallels, which show similar panels with lions and palm trees. The specific combination of cherubim with lions and palms (all three motifs appearing together) appears at Megiddo in the 10th-century ivory carvings: the Megiddo ivories show a king on a sphinx/cherub throne flanked by palm trees with lions at the base. The Solomonic bronze stands carried the same tripartite iconographic program in a different medium (cast bronze vs. carved ivory), confirming that the stand decoration drew on the standard Syro-Palestinian royal iconography of the period.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The production of ten identical stands through a single casting process (<em>mûṣāq ʾeḥāḏ</em>, one casting/one mold-type) demonstrates the standardization capacity of Hiram's workshop. Producing ten identical bronze objects at this scale — each 4 × 4 × 3 cubits — required a standardized clay-mold system with consistent dimensions. Ancient bronze foundries used master patterns (wood or stone) to produce multiple identical clay molds, enabling batch production. The Jordan Valley casting site (v46) would have required a temporary foundry installation for this project — furnaces, clay beds, and cooling trenches appropriate for the scale of production.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The ten bronze lavers (one per stand, each 40-bath capacity) provided the water for washing burnt offerings (2 Chr 4:6). The placement of five on the south side and five on the north (v39) created a bilateral symmetry around the Temple, with the lavers positioned near the burnt offering altar where washing would occur. The 40-bath capacity of each laver (approximately 240 gallons, approximately 900 liters) provided ample water for a day's sacrificial service without requiring constant refilling from the great Sea. The laver system was the Temple's practical water-management infrastructure, designed for sustained high-volume ritual operation during festival periods.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The spatial arrangement of the Temple court furnishings — five stands on the south, five on the north, the Sea at the southeast corner — reflects a carefully designed liturgical geography. The Temple faced east (entrance on the east); the great Sea at the southeast positioned the priests' purification basin adjacent to both the Temple entrance and the burnt offering altar's south side. The bilateral symmetry of the ten lavers (five south, five north) ensured equal access from both sides of the large court. The deliberate spatial organization of all the Temple court furnishings indicates a thoughtful liturgical planning process, not merely ad hoc placement.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The completion summary of Hiram's bronze work identifies the three functional vessel types: lavers (<em>kiyyōrôṯ</em>), pots (<em>yᵉʿîm</em>), and basins (<em>mizrāqôṯ</em>). The pots were used for ash removal from the burnt offering altar (Exod 27:3 uses the same term for the tabernacle's ash-pots); the basins were used to catch and sprinkle blood at the altar. These three types cover the complete functional range of the outer court's priestly service. Hiram's completion of all assigned bronze work — a project of extraordinary scale for any single craftsman's workshop — confirms that he directed a team of skilled Phoenician bronze-workers, not a solo operation.</p>",
    "41": "<p>The summary inventory of bronze work (vv41-47) follows the standard ANE building-inscription format: construction description, then summary inventory for accountability and archival purposes. Assyrian and Babylonian temple building inscriptions consistently include inventory summaries listing all objects made, their materials, and quantities. The Solomonic inventory served the same function: an official Temple archive record confirming what had been made and installed, against which future inspections and inventories could be checked. The later temple inventories (2 Kgs 24:13; 25:13-17) confirm that such records were maintained.</p>",
    "42": "<p>The 400-pomegranate total (200 per pillar) confirmed in the summary inventory is independently verified by Jeremiah's description of the pillars being dismantled and taken to Babylon (Jer 52:22-23). This cross-verification between the building account, the inventory summary, and the destruction account demonstrates the historical reliability of the Kings building narrative — the same objects described in detail in ch 7 appear by name in the Babylonian looting account 350 years later. The bronze pillars were among the most valuable and recognizable objects from the Temple, worth explicitly recording both at their installation and at their removal.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The ten-stand and ten-laver units are summarized together as functional pairs, consistent with their original installation. The 1:1 ratio of stands to lavers created a modular system where each unit could function independently — important for Temple operations during festivals when the large volume of sacrifices required all ten laver stations operating simultaneously. The Passover sacrifice (requiring the slaughter and washing of thousands of animals) or the dedication sacrifices (22,000 cattle and 120,000 sheep, 8:63) would have needed all ten laver stations and the full court water system operating at capacity.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The Sea and its twelve oxen are summarized as a single unit, acknowledging that the twelve oxen were not decorative pedestals but structural supports integral to the Sea's installation. The removal of the Sea to Babylon in 605/586 BCE (2 Kgs 25:13; Jer 52:17) required dismantling the ox base as well — the Babylonian account of removing 'the bronze sea that was in the house of the LORD' confirms that the Sea survived from Solomon to Nebuchadnezzar (approximately 350 years), a remarkable testimony to the quality of Hiram's bronze-casting work.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The 'burnished bronze' (<em>nᵉḥōšeṯ mᵉmōrāṭ</em>) finish of all Hiram's vessels indicates that each piece was polished to a mirror finish after casting. Ancient bronze was buffed with abrasives (sandstone, pumice) to a reflective surface that resisted tarnishing and was easy to clean. The aesthetic dimension of this work — every functional vessel polished to gleaming — reflects the Temple's overall design philosophy: even working tools were beautiful. This commitment to beauty in functionality parallels the tabernacle's construction, where every object, including the pots and shovels, was made of precious materials (Exod 38:3: bronze for all tabernacle vessels).</p>",
    "46": "<p>The Jordan Valley casting site between Succoth and Zarethan is in the central Jordan Valley, approximately 35-40 miles northeast of Jerusalem. The region's abundant clay deposits (noted in the text: <em>bᵉmaʿăbēh hāʾădāmāh</em>, in the clay ground) provided ideal material for the large bronze-casting molds required. The region's timber resources (Jordan Valley had extensive woodland in the Iron Age) supplied the fuel for the sustained high-temperature smelting needed. The pre-industrial logistics of transporting the finished bronze objects from the Jordan Valley to Jerusalem involved ox-cart transport on the steep Judean ascent — a logistical achievement comparable to the cedar transport from Lebanon.</p>",
    "47": "<p>The notation that the bronze weight was 'not determined' because the quantity was too great contrasts with the careful weight-recording of the tabernacle materials (Exod 38:21-31, which gives the weight of every metal used). The tabernacle, made in the wilderness with limited resources, required strict accountability of every ounce. Solomon's Temple, made at the height of the empire's prosperity, had such abundant bronze that weighing it was impractical. The contrast communicates the scale of Solomon's building resources — not careless accounting, but wealth too great to require the same scrutiny as wilderness-era scarcity.</p>",
    "48": "<p>The transition from bronze (outer court furnishings) to gold (inner Temple furnishings) in v48 marks the spatial transition from the accessible outer court to the restricted inner Temple. The golden altar (<em>mizbaḥ hazzāhāḇ</em>) was the incense altar — the direct functional successor to the tabernacle's incense altar (Exod 30:1-10). Its placement before the entrance to the Holy of Holies made it the last object in the priests' daily ritual sequence: after the lampstands were trimmed and the bread of the Presence was set, incense was burned on the golden altar as the fragrant climax of the morning service. The incense represented the prayers of Israel ascending to YHWH (Ps 141:2; Rev 5:8).</p>",
    "49": "<p>The ten golden lampstands (five north, five south of the entrance to the debir) replaced and multiplied the tabernacle's single seven-branched menorah. The tabernacle menorah (Exod 25:31-40) was a single lampstand; the Temple's ten lampstands extended the priestly light throughout the wider main hall. Josephus (Antiquities 8.90) describes the Temple's lampstands as resembling the tabernacle's menorah design, though ten in number. The lampstands were among the first objects taken in the Babylonian looting (2 Kgs 24:13) — portable, gold, and recognizable as cult objects of enormous value. The later Temple Menorah looted by Rome (70 CE) appears on the Arch of Titus in Rome, confirming that the lampstand tradition persisted through the Second Temple period.</p>",
    "50": "<p>The complete catalog of gold furnishings (flower decorations, lamp equipment, tongs, cups, snuffers, basins, dishes, and fire-holders) reflects the functional equipment for daily priestly service at the lampstands and incense altar. All of pure gold (<em>zāhāb sāgûr</em>) — even the most mundane implements (tongs, snuffers) were made of the same refined gold as the structural furnishings. The ANE principle that objects proximate to the divine must share in the divine quality of perfection (gold = incorruptibility, purity, divine nature) governed the choice of materials for every implement, regardless of its routine function.</p>",
    "51": "<p>The transfer of David's dedicated treasures (silver, gold, and vessels accumulated over his reign for the Temple project) completed the building project's closure. David had explicitly prohibited from building the Temple himself (2 Sam 7:12-13; 1 Chr 22:8) but had spent his reign preparing everything needed — materials, craftsmen, plans, and accumulated wealth. 1 Chr 22:14 records David's contribution: 100,000 talents of gold, 1,000,000 talents of silver (numbers likely hyperbolic or using different weight standards), along with bronze, iron, timber, and stone beyond measure. The transfer of these materials to the Temple treasury completed the Davidic-Solomonic building partnership: the king who could not build prepared everything; the king who built consumed what his father had prepared. The Temple was the product of two generations of covenant purpose.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '1kings')
    merge_comm(c, KINGS1)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1kings', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in KINGS1.values())
    print(f'1 Kings 6–7 mkt-context: {count} verses written')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
